The threshold dependence becomes even clearer on the held-out test set. For Level 2, the predictive exceedance probability under 131 MPa is 0.8274, compared with 0.8476 from the posterior mean alone and 0.8293 from the ground-truth stress values. When the threshold is reduced from 131 to 120 and 110 MPa, the predictive exceedance probability rises from 0.8274 to 0.9036 and 0.9553, respectively. The corresponding mean predicted stress is 162.60 MPa, close to the true mean of 162.96 MPa, with an average predictive stress uncertainty of 8.68 MPa. These results show that risk is not equivalent to variance or mean shift alone; instead, it is a threshold-dependent transformation of the predictive distribution. \uc0\u12304 The engineering basis of the 131 MPa threshold should still be stated formally in Methods or Supplementary Information.\u12305  \
